Deere & Company (NYSE:DE) Shares Sold by IBM Retirement Fund


					Posted by Harper Lund on Jul 16th, 2017 // No Comments




IBM Retirement Fund lowered its position in shares of  Deere & Company (NYSE:DE) by 88.1% during the first quarter, according to its most recent filing with the Securities and Exchange Commission. The firm owned 3,511 shares of the industrial products company’s stock after selling 26,038 shares during the period. IBM Retirement Fund’s holdings in Deere & Company were worth $510,000 at the end of the most recent reporting period. 
A number of other hedge funds and other institutional investors have also recently modified their holdings of the stock. PGGM Investments bought a new stake in shares of  Deere & Company during the first quarter worth $26,179,000.  Dodge & Cox acquired a new position in  Deere & Company during the fourth quarter valued at $2,678,000.  Nordea Investment Management AB boosted its position in  Deere & Company by 1.1% in the first quarter. Nordea Investment Management AB now owns 124,936 shares of the industrial products company’s stock valued at $13,601,000 after buying an additional 1,342 shares in the last quarter.  Vident Investment Advisory LLC boosted its position in  Deere & Company by 6.2% in the fourth quarter. Vident Investment Advisory LLC now owns 12,901 shares of the industrial products company’s stock valued at $1,329,000 after buying an additional 753 shares in the last quarter.  Finally, Quadrature Capital Ltd acquired a new position in  Deere & Company during the fourth quarter valued at $26,810,000. Hedge funds and other institutional investors own  67.35% of the company’s stock. 


 Get Deere & Company alerts:



Deere & Company (DE) traded up 0.84% during midday trading on Friday, hitting $125.47. 1,776,971 shares of the stock were exchanged. The firm has a market capitalization of $40.13 billion, a P/E ratio of 22.61 and a beta of 0.66. The firm’s 50-day moving average price is $122.43 and its 200 day moving average price is $111.76. Deere & Company has a 1-year low of $76.73 and a 1-year high of $129.00. 





Deere & Company (NYSE:DE) last posted its quarterly earnings results on Friday, May 19th. The industrial products company reported $2.49 earnings per share for the quarter, topping the Zacks’ consensus estimate of $1.70 by $0.79. The business had revenue of $7.26 billion during the quarter, compared to analyst estimates of $7.27 billion. Deere & Company had a net margin of 6.52% and a return on equity of 24.85%. The company’s revenue was up 2.2% on a year-over-year basis. During the same period in the prior year, the business posted $1.56 earnings per share.  Analysts expect that  Deere & Company will post $6.29 earnings per share for the current fiscal year. 
The company also recently declared a quarterly dividend, which will be paid on Tuesday, August 1st. Shareholders of record on Friday, June 30th will be given a $0.60 dividend. The ex-dividend date is Wednesday, June 28th. This represents a $2.40 dividend on an annualized basis and a dividend yield of 1.91%. Deere & Company’s payout ratio is currently 43.24%. 
TRADEMARK VIOLATION WARNING: “Deere & Company (NYSE:DE) Shares Sold by IBM Retirement Fund” was originally  posted by Chaffey Breeze and is owned by of Chaffey Breeze. If you are viewing this story on another publication, it was stolen and republished in violation of U.S. & international trademark and copyright law. The correct version of this story can be viewed at https://www.chaffeybreeze.com/2017/07/16/deere-company-nysede-shares-sold-by-ibm-retirement-fund-updated.html. 
Several brokerages recently issued reports on DE. Citigroup Inc. boosted their price target on Deere & Company from $145.00 to $150.00 and gave the company a “buy” rating in a research note on Friday, June 9th. BidaskClub upgraded Deere & Company from a “buy” rating to a “strong-buy” rating in a research note on Saturday, June 10th. Barclays PLC  set a $100.00 price objective on Deere & Company and gave the company a “sell” rating in a research note on Sunday, June 4th. Jefferies Group LLC  restated a “hold” rating and set a $125.00 price target on shares of Deere & Company in a research report on Thursday, July 6th. Finally, Credit Suisse Group  set a $151.00 price target on Deere & Company and gave the stock a “buy” rating in a research report on Saturday, June 3rd. Three research analysts have rated the stock with a sell rating, fourteen have given a hold rating and eleven have given a buy rating to the company. The company  has a consensus rating of “Hold” and an average target price of $122.24.
In related news, insider Cory J. Reed sold 4,936 shares of the company’s stock in a transaction on Friday, June 16th. The shares were sold at an average price of $128.00, for a total transaction of $631,808.00. Following the sale, the insider now owns 9,903 shares of the company’s stock, valued at $1,267,584. The transaction was disclosed in a legal filing with the SEC, which is available through the SEC website. Also, CEO Samuel R. Allen sold 62,704 shares of the company’s stock in a transaction on Thursday, June 1st. The shares were sold at an average price of $125.00, for a total transaction of $7,838,000.00. Following the sale, the chief executive officer now directly owns 333,492 shares in the company, valued at approximately $41,686,500. The disclosure for this sale can be found here. Over the last quarter, insiders sold 105,612 shares of company stock valued at $13,149,023. Company insiders own  0.85% of the company’s stock. 
About Deere & Company
Deere & Company is engaged in equipment operations. The Company is engaged in providing financial services. The Company operates through three business segments: agriculture and turf, construction and forestry, and financial services. The agriculture and turf segment manufactures and distributes a line of agriculture and turf equipment and related service parts.







