Big Blue's Pension Makeover
IBM's pension team has restructured $79 billion in
      global assets to cut costs, improve returns, and make IBM
      pension plans in 45 countries work more closely together.
      Here's how.
By Randy Myers  | February 1998  





















  














IBM's pension team has
        restructured $79 billion in global assets to cut costs,
        improve returns, and make IBM pension plans in 45 countries
        work more closely together. Here's how.A cold February day in 1994 may have been the most
        traumatic of Tom Cadigan's career. Shortly after the
        25-year-veteran IBM executive walked into the offices of
        the IBM Retirement Funds in Stamford, Connecticut, he and a
        senior colleague met quietly with 50 of their co-pension
        staffers, one-on-one, to tell them their jobs had been
        eliminated."It was very difficult," recalls Cadigan, who four
        months later was named an assistant treasurer of IBM and
        managing director of IBM Retirement Funds, one of the
        world's largest pension operations. "We were 70 people
        planning to go to 100, and overnight we went to 20," he
        says. "Obviously, we had to change our priorities."Change indeed, or sink. Eleven months earlier, Lou
        Gerstner, the hard-charging executive who had turned around
        RJR Nabisco-and downsized its corporate and pension
        operations in the process-had taken the reins of
        then-struggling IBM. After bringing aboard Chrysler's Jerry
        York, a renowned cost-cutter, as his CFO, the two went to
        work reducing costs and focusing the computer giant's
        attention on its core competencies, shedding or outsourcing
        everything else.Active, in-house management of pension assets was not
        one of Big Blue's core competencies. Gerstner and New York
        concluded that the entire pension operation, one of the
        biggest in the US, could be run more efficiently and
        successfully, and with less risk, if they outsourced the
        task."There were three fundamental factors behind the
        decision [to reduce the pension staff], and core competency
        was actually the lesser of the three," explains York, now
        vice chairman of investor Kirk Kerkorian's Tracinda
        Corporation.The more important factor, to York's mind, was
        eliminating the risk of internal error or even
        sabotage-although he stresses that he had absolutely no
        reason to think that anybody on board at that time would
        engage in such activity. "I am just a lot more comfortable,
        if there is a problem, in having [it come from] some
        external manager in a fiduciary position-someone working
        for a firm that has the proverbial deep pockets, with the
        appropriate bonding capacity and insurance policies, that
        will allow you to recover," York says."The [third] factor was that I think it's incredibly
        difficult to outperform the market," he adds. "And the more
        managers you have internally, the more difficult it is to
        do that, because some are going to overperform and some are
        going to underperform. That was the nubbin."Tom Cadigan joined IBM in 1969, and has enjoyed a
        sparkling career. After spending 12 years in operational
        finance-including seven at IBM Europe's Paris
        headquarters-he moved to Treasury for 10 years before
        joining the IBM Retirement Funds. In the office, he is both
        formal and gracious.Change of dutiesThe story of how he and his small team of 19 additional
        professionals-plus five support staff-coped with the
        restructuring shows how a pension team can change itself
        for the better, even during a difficult downsizing. IBM's
        trim new pension operation has posted benchmark-beating
        investment returns since 1994. And it has done so with
        leading-edge attention to risk management that helped earn
        it a rare "superior" rating in a tough, corporate-wide
        audit last year."They are as disciplined and focused on risk control as
        any large pension fund I work with," says Thomas Healey,
        managing director in charge of pension services at Goldman
        Sachs, which is one of the IBM Retirement Funds' brokers
        and also manages portions of its fixed income and real
        estate portfolios. "It is a hallmark of the way they run
        their business, and it goes through everything they
        do."Actual operating costs at the IBM Retirement Funds have
        not declined as a result of the downsizing: Outside vendors
        are almost always more costly than employees, after all.
        But the reorganization did allow-if not force-Cadigan and
        his team to focus on the goal most important to the parent
        company: beating the fund's benchmark while controlling
        risk.New priorities meant deep changes in how the
        slimmed-down pension staff operates. Cadigan put a senior
        member of his team, global funds management director RL
        "Jay" Vivian, in charge of risk management, and reviewed
        and tightened risk controls from top to bottom. To leverage
        IBM's pension expertise in the US and 44 foreign countries,
        he encouraged greater sharing of information by
        consolidating custodial operations worldwide among a
        handful of global custody banks. And, with its US
        custodian, IBM developed a central information source
        accessible to all of its pension operations worldwide.Cadigan also leveraged his group's established expertise
        in passive equity management to control trading costs. And
        finally, the IBM Retirement Funds team moved to a
        significantly greater reliance on passive money management.
        Today, about 60% of assets are indexed, versus 45% before
        1994."Tom Cadigan pulled together a group of people in
        circumstances where there was turbulence and chaos, and now
        has them working as a team headed in the same direction,"
        says IBM treasurer Jeffrey Serkes.The payoff: Net of fees, IBM's US defined benefit plan
        posted an 18.4% total return over the three years ended
        last September, or 160 basis points over its benchmark,
        which is an amalgam of indices reflecting the various asset
        classes in which it invests (see chart, right). Its numbers
        were even more impressive for the 12 months ended in
        September, when its 25.5% total return exceeded the
        benchmark by 330 basis points. A key contributor has been
        stellar returns in fixed income, due partly to some
        well-placed bets on high yield and emerging markets debt,
        which have outpaced Treasuries and investment-grade
        corporates in recent years.Helped in part by the solid investment returns, plan
        assets climbed from $28.2 billion at the end of 1993 to $40
        billion after last year's third quarter. Over the same
        period, assets in IBM's 401(k) plan grew from $6.8 billion
        to $14 billion. Combined with some $25 billion in both
        defined benefit and defined contribution assets at its
        non-US subsidiaries-a greater international pension
        presence than any other US company-IBM now has a total of
        $79 billion under management. That makes it one of the four
        largest private US pension sponsors, along with fellow
        corporate icons General Motors, AT&T, and General
        Electric.Changing liabilitiesThe winnowing of IBM's pension management team could
        hardly have come at a more critical time. Nineteen
        ninety-four would prove a rotten year for the financial
        markets. As they wrestled with how to increase returns,
        Cadigan and his team also had to accommodate a dramatic
        change in the nature of their liabilities.In 1985, Big Blue's workforce had peaked at 406,000. By
        the end of 1994 it had dwindled to just under 220,000-a 45%
        decline. Employment has grown again since then, to nearly
        250,000. The company had 193,000 active participants in its
        defined benefit plan in 1991, and 94,000 inactive. By the
        end of 1996, it had 118,000 active participants and 187,000
        inactive."Ten years ago, 70% of the net present value of our
        [defined benefit plan] liabilities were associated with
        active, younger employees," confirms James Rich, the
        retirement funds' senior investment strategist. "Now, 80%
        of our liability is associated with non-active
        employees.""We're paying about $1.5 billion a year in benefits,"
        adds Cadigan. "Ten years ago, what we paid in benefits was
        almost not a consideration." One result: a new level of
        attention to risk."When we started," says Vivian, who also enforces money
        manager guidelines, "we defined risk management as
        monitoring unintended investment risks, such as derivatives
        exposures of the sort that made headlines at Procter &
        Gamble and Gibson Greetings in 1994. But we soon recognized
        that there are many other risks, and that they encompass
        our entire operations, from things such as network security
        and physical security to IT [information technology]
        support."Lowering trading costsOne of the biggest concentrations of pension assets in
        the world-some $104 billion-is run out of 3001-3003 Summer
        Street, an unpretentious but striking seven-story structure
        in downtown Stamford, Connecticut. IBM Retirement Funds is
        housed on the first floor of that dual-address building,
        downstairs from GE Investments, the $50 billion pension
        management arm of General Electric Company, which also
        manages $19 billion for outside investors. Similar in size
        and prestige, the two operations could hardly be more
        different in other ways.GE manages the vast majority of its assets internally,
        relying on its own research staff and its unique access to
        GE managers in diverse industries to find attractive
        investments (see "Plan Sponsor Profile," Plan Sponsor, May
        1997). IBM today farms out its entire actively managed
        portfolio. IBM Retirement Funds has outsourced other
        functions as well, such as tracking dividends and making
        sure they are paid on time.In the end, Cadigan thinks the net value-excess return
        minus the cost-that his team gets is still the best. That
        claim is borne out by Toronto-based consultant Cost
        Effective Management, which surveys pension sponsors to
        measure the effectiveness of their investment policy
        decisions and calculate a value-added comparison. A CEM
        survey shows IBM in the top 20% of the 12 largest funds for
        the past three years, and in the top 12% of CEM's entire
        157-fund universe.One reason: a heavy focus on controlling costs in its
        investment program. Since the end of 1994, IBM has reduced
        its contingent of outside money managers to 50 from 66. It
        now outsources its actively managed equities, fixed income,
        real estate, and private investments.But IBM continues to run passive equity management, or
        indexing, internally. This is for two reasons: First,
        internal portfolio management director Charles Maxfield's
        indexing group, which runs about 50% of the fund's total
        equities, has proven it can do the job as well as anybody,
        and for less cost. For example, IBM's Standard & Poor's
        500 index portfolio costs less than 1 basis point annually
        to run.More importantly, keeping the index operation in-house
        allows IBM to avoid trading costs. Maxfield and his staff
        have ready and virtually cost-free access to most
        securities its active managers might want to buy or sell
        when they make portfolio changes, or when their
        relationship with IBM is initiated or terminated."I call Charlie the gearbox of the fund," Cadigan says
        of Maxfield. "If we would decide to shift more money to
        international equities and less to domestic equities, just
        to use an example, we would run that through Charlie's
        group. If we hire a new manager, we take the stocks from
        the old manager, give them to Charlie, and then ask the new
        manager what stocks he would like to start off with in his
        portfolio. We will cut them out of Charlie's holdings and
        hand the manager a portfolio that's ready to go on the day
        we start the clock running. That activity alone saves us
        tens of millions of dollars a year. We not only avoid
        transaction costs, but the costs associated with market
        impact."Managing other portfolio shifts efficiently this way
        takes real size, since raiding your index portfolio can
        temporarily throw its carefully constructed composition out
        of whack. But for a plan of IBM's bulk, that impact is
        quite modest. With some $12 billion allocated to passive
        equity management, IBM Retirement Funds is already one of
        the world's largest indexers of US and non-US equities
        alike.Now, Cadigan is starting to leverage Maxfield's
        expertise further by allowing him to manage both domestic
        and international passive equity for some of IBM's overseas
        pension plans. And Maxfield's group is branching out into
        enhanced indexing. In May 1996, Cadigan permitted one of
        Maxfield's bright young assistants, senior portfolio
        manager Scott Baum, to launch a modest-now $150
        million-enhanced index portfolio benchmarked against the
        Russell 3000."It's not an active stock-picking account," Cadigan
        says. "A pure Russell 3000 index fund would have to own
        3,000 stocks, and even pure indexers don't do that-it would
        be very expensive and inflexible. So everybody uses
        optimizers, which is taking you one step away from pure
        indexing. And this is just one more step."Big Blue also leverages its buying power to help its
        401(k) plan. Rather than choosing from popular but
        expensive mutual funds sold to retail investors, IBM's
        401(k) participants select from a menu of company stock
        plus seven core funds and four "Life Strategy" funds, the
        latter tailored to participants with varying investment
        objectives and levels of risk tolerance. IBM chose to use
        institutional money managers when it launched the plan in
        1982, and in recent years this has proved to be an
        appealing strategy to other large employers that want to
        cut costs and extend proven managers' services to the
        401(k) side (see "All together now," Plan Sponsor,
        December/January 1998).The result: IBM plan participants enjoy their 401(k)
        benefits at a total cost-management plus administrative
        fees-of just 11 basis points, with only about a quarter of
        that amount going to money managers. By contrast, many
        popular mutual funds charge management fees that alone
        exceed 100 basis points.A push to outperformWhile Maxfield seeks to match the Russell 3000, senior
        investment manager Robert Ploder strives to beat the index
        by 100 basis points, net of costs, limiting his overall
        tracking error to 200 basis points. Ploder is a manager of
        managers: He oversees 15 firms that actively run $6 billion
        of the IBM Retirement Funds' domestic equities.Those managers have collectively fallen short of their
        performance goal over the past three years. But they have
        improved recently, outpacing the Russell by 30 basis points
        for the 12 months ended September 30 and 120 basis points
        in third quarter 1997. One reason why is that Ploder likes
        to take small bets on a wide spectrum of stocks rather than
        concentrating on a few broad market sectors. And large-cap
        issues finally surrendered their market leadership role
        during the third quarter to mid-cap and small-cap
        stocks.IBM tries to limit the tilt in either direction-growth
        versus value or large-cap versus small-cap-to a total
        tracking error of no more than 100 basis points. This
        contributes to risk control, says Ploder, a veteran Wall
        Street analyst and money manager before joining IBM six
        years ago. It also reflects the fact that IBM is not trying
        to time market style or size moves, he says.While IBM's active equity managers have been benchmark
        stragglers, their fixed income counterparts have been on a
        tear. In aggregate, IBM's $10 billion in domestic fixed
        income portfolios posted average annualized returns of
        11.7% for the three years ended in September, or a whopping
        222 basis points more than the benchmark Lehman Brothers
        Aggregate index.Credit is shared by IBM's 14 outside bond managers and
        by Jae Park, senior investment manager, who oversees the
        fixed income side. Park uses managers with a variety of
        investment styles, to keep their aggregate tracking error
        versus the Lehman under 100 basis points. To prevent any
        surprises, he requires them to submit regular reports
        identifying key risk factors in their portfolios, including
        effective duration, yield curve risk, sector weightings and
        duration, and credit quality. And every month, a consultant
        in San Francisco runs a risk and performance attribution
        analysis on each manager to keep Park on top of any shifts
        in his fixed income porfolios.Park has also written proprietary software for the IBM
        Retirement Funds, with which he and his colleagues evaluate
        their active money managers. As refined by Ray Kanner, the
        funds' global equity manager, the software produces what
        IBM calls Performance Evaluation Profiles, or "PEP charts."
        A cornucopia of statistics, these show how active managers
        have performed in various investment environments and
        compare their risk/performance tradeoffs.Pulling together globallyCadigan wants more of this kind of knowledge sharing.
        Under his leadership, the pension team is leveraging the
        tools and skill sets it developed for the domestic
        portfolio to help improve management of its $14 billion
        domestic 401(k) plan and of its foreign subsidiaries'
        pension plans.The treasury officials who run pension plans at IBM's
        affiliates in 44 countries outside the US-the largest, IBM
        Germany, has about $7 billion in assets, while five other
        plans have over $1 billion-do not report to Cadigan.
        Instead, they typically report to one of three regional
        treasurers based in Big Blue's European, Latin American,
        and Asia Pacific regional treasury centers, who in turn
        report to treasurer Serkes.But the company's far-flung foreign pension chiefs do
        rely on Cadigan and his staff for advice-and, in some
        cases, more.Cadigan's office manages an S&P 500 index fund for
        IBM Germany, and two portfolios for IBM Canada indexed
        against the Morgan Stanley Capital International's US index
        and the MSCI World index.No cookie-cutter solutions work for all the IBM plans:
        Spanning 44 foreign countries-some with more than one
        plan-each has different fiduciary, regulatory, and legal
        standards to meet, not to mention different benefit levels
        and payment schemes.Instead of looking for one-size-fits-all answers,
        Cadigan and Serkes have focused on developing what they
        call a "virtual" investment management organization,
        independent of IBM's organizational lines. When IBM
        Netherlands needs a European equity manager, for example,
        it does not make sense to ignore work that IBM Germany
        might have already done in that area-or vice versa.Making all new manager selections today are a team of
        representatives from an IBM unit in a major country outside
        the US, the US fund, and a regional support group. Cadigan
        and his team also hold "Pension University," a twice-a-year
        seminar that hosts about 10 professionals from IBM offices
        around the world. And they communicate frequently with
        IBM's foreign pension chiefs through the company's Lotus
        Notes email system and videoconferencing.Key to this information sharing effort has been the
        formation of a network of global custody banks. Currently,
        Chase Manhattan Bank is custodian for the US and German
        plans, while State Street Bank & Trust and Northern
        Trust split duties for the other non-US pension funds.
        These banks perform most of the accounting and
        administrative chores that IBM Retirement Funds performed
        in-house before it restructured in early 1994.Chase also provides IBM with an innovative product
        called Master Record Keeper, or "MRK," a central repository
        from which Cadigan and his staff can access data from any
        Big Blue pension plan worldwide (see "Pushing the data
        frontier," Plan Sponsor, July/August 1997). Developed with
        much input from the client, the system supplies information
        including performance and performance attribution data at
        any level that IBM desires, down to individual
        securities."The Master Record Keeper allows us to take scarce IBM
        staff out of the report preparation business and focus them
        more on investment management, where they can add a lot
        more value," adds Cadigan. "It also provides a common
        database of fund and manager performance which we all have
        access to and use."The futureHas IBM achieved its pension goals? Cadigan and his team
        continue to push for enhanced global coordination among
        IBM's pension plans throughout the world. The Stamford
        staff see opportunities for more cooperation in the use of
        consultants, actuarial services, staffing, and systems, to
        name only a few examples. They also are expanding their
        focus on expense control and continuing to refine their
        risk and information management systems. And on the
        investment side, they are paying increased attention to the
        asset-liability dynamic.No immediate crisis looms. Rich calculates the US plan's
        liabilities out to the year 2062 at $87 billion, although
        their net present value is only about $30 billion. That, of
        course, is about $10 billion less than plan assets, a
        circumstance appreciated at IBM headquarters in Armonk, New
        York.IBM was last forced to make a contribution to its
        defined benefit plan in 1995. Treasurer Serkes says its
        current overfunded position indicates that IBM should not
        have to make any additional contributions "certainly for
        five to 10 years, and probably longer than that."All of which pleases IBM's treasurer. "I'm happy with
        the performance of our retirement funds and with the
        people," he concludes. "And I'm also happy with their
        attitude-not just in the US but around the world, where
        people have come to appreciate that we have real expertise.
        And they're starting to leverage the resources we
        have."



